h1. WorkSpaces User Provisioning Runbook

h2. Overview

This runbook guides you through the complete process of provisioning a new user with an Amazon WorkSpace. By the end, you'll have:
* A new Active Directory user account
* The user added to the correct security groups (including local admin rights)
* A WorkSpace deployed and assigned to that user

*Estimated Time:* 15-20 minutes

----

h2. Prerequisites

Before starting, ensure you have:

{status:colour=Grey|title=Access to the Ansible control machine (your local Mac with the repos)}
{status:colour=Grey|title=AWS CLI configured with appropriate permissions}
{status:colour=Grey|title=Access to the cloud_infrastructure repository}
{status:colour=Grey|title=The user's information (name, email, desired username)}

*Repository Locations:*
||Project||Path||
|AD Management|{{~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/account-111122223333}}|
|WorkSpaces|{{~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/org-workspaces-vdi}}|

----

h2. Step 1: Create the AD User Account

h3. Option A: Using the Ansible Playbook (Recommended)

{panel:title=Step 1.1 - Navigate to the AD project|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ccc}
{code:language=bash}
cd ~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/account-111122223333/ansible
{code}
{panel}

{panel:title=Step 1.2 - Edit the users file|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ccc}
{code:language=bash}
vim playbooks/user-management/users.yml
{code}
{panel}

{panel:title=Step 1.3 - Add the new user entry|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ccc}
{code:language=yaml}
ad_users:
  # ... existing users ...
  
  - username: <username>                # Login name (no spaces, lowercase)
    display_name: "<Full Name>"         # Full name as it appears in AD
    password: "{{ default_password }}"  # Uses default password from vars
    email: "<username>@example.internal"         # Email address
    groups:
      - "Domain Users"
      - "WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins"        # IMPORTANT: Gives local admin on WorkSpace
    description: "Standard user account"
    must_change_password: false         # Set to true if user should change password on first login
{code}
{panel}

{panel:title=Step 1.4 - Save and run the playbook|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ccc}
Save the file ({{:wq}} in vim), then run:
{code:language=bash}
ansible-playbook playbooks/user-management/manage-users.yml -v
{code}
{panel}

{panel:title=Step 1.5 - Verify the user was created|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ccc}
{code:language=bash}
ansible-playbook playbooks/user-management/list-users.yml
{code}
{panel}

h3. Option B: Create User with Custom Password

If you want to specify a password instead of using the default:
{code:language=bash}
ansible-playbook playbooks/user-management/manage-users.yml -e "default_password=<YOUR_SECURE_PASSWORD>"
{code}

{info:title=Password Information}
*Default Password Location:* The default password is defined in {{playbooks/user-management/users.yml}} in the {{default_password}} variable.

*Credentials Storage:* All production credentials are stored in AWS Secrets Manager:
* *Secret Name:* {{org-infrastructure/credentials}}
* *Region:* {{us-east-2}}

To retrieve credentials:
{code:language=bash}
aws secretsmanager get-secret-value \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --secret-id org-infrastructure/credentials \
  --query SecretString --output text | jq .
{code}
{info}

----

h2. Step 2: Verify User Configuration

h3. Check User Details

Run this command to verify the user was created correctly:
{code:language=bash}
CMD_ID=$(aws ssm send-command \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --instance-ids i-0e5f7fdd4219cc530 \
  --document-name "AWS-RunPowerShellScript" \
  --parameters 'commands=["Get-ADUser -Identity <USERNAME> -Properties DisplayName,EmailAddress,MemberOf | Format-List"]' \
  --output json | jq -r '.Command.CommandId') && \
sleep 5 && \
aws ssm get-command-invocation \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --command-id $CMD_ID \
  --instance-id i-0e5f7fdd4219cc530 \
  --query "StandardOutputContent" \
  --output text
{code}

{note}
Replace {{<USERNAME>}} with the actual username you created.
{note}

h3. Expected Output

You should see:
* {{DisplayName}} matches what you entered
* {{EmailAddress}} is correct
* {{MemberOf}} includes:
** {{CN=Domain Users,CN=Users,DC=example,DC=internal}}
** {{CN=WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins,OU=Groups,DC=example,DC=internal}}

h3. Troubleshooting: Add User to LocalAdmins Group Manually

If the user is missing from {{WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins}}:
{code:language=bash}
aws ssm send-command \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --instance-ids i-0e5f7fdd4219cc530 \
  --document-name "AWS-RunPowerShellScript" \
  --parameters 'commands=["Add-ADGroupMember -Identity \"WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins\" -Members \"<USERNAME>\""]' \
  --output json
{code}

----

h2. Step 3: Deploy the WorkSpace

h3. 3.1 Navigate to WorkSpaces Project

{code:language=bash}
cd ~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/org-workspaces-vdi
{code}

h3. 3.2 Edit the Terraform Variables

{code:language=bash}
vim terraform.tfvars
{code}

h3. 3.3 Add the New User to the WorkSpaces List

Find the {{workspaces_users}} section and add the new user:
{code:language=hcl}
workspaces_users = [
  # Existing users...
  
  {
    username    = "<username>"       # Must match the AD username exactly
    bundle_id   = "wsb-09fdsggz9"    # Standard Windows 10 bundle
    volume_encryption_enabled = true
    user_volume_size = 50            # User drive size in GB
    root_volume_size = 80            # System drive size in GB
    tags = {
      Department = "<Department>"    # Optional: customize as needed
      Owner      = "<Full Name>"
    }
  }
]
{code}

h3. 3.4 Save and Apply Terraform

{code:language=bash}
# Preview what will be created
terraform plan

# Apply the changes (creates the WorkSpace)
terraform apply
{code}

Type {{yes}} when prompted to confirm.

h3. 3.5 Wait for WorkSpace Provisioning

{warning}
WorkSpace provisioning takes approximately *15-20 minutes*.
{warning}

You can monitor progress in the AWS Console:
# Go to AWS Console → WorkSpaces
# Select the *ap-southeast-1* region (or us-east-2 depending on deployment)
# Find the new WorkSpace in the list
# Status will progress: {{PENDING}} → {{STARTING}} → {{AVAILABLE}}

----

h2. Step 4: Post-Deployment Configuration

Once the WorkSpace is {{AVAILABLE}}, the following happens automatically via GPO:

h3. Automatic Configurations (via Group Policy)

||Configuration||Description||
|Local Admin Rights|User is added to local Administrators group (from WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins membership)|
|S3 Installers Drive|S: drive is mounted with access to software installers|

h3. Verify Local Admin Rights

After the user logs in, they can verify admin rights:
# Open PowerShell as the user
# Run: {{net localgroup Administrators}}
# Should see {{ORG\WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins}} or the username in the list

----

h2. Step 5: Provide User with Login Information

Send the following information to the new user:

{panel:title=Email Template for New User|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#0052CC|bgColor=#E6FCFF}
Your Amazon WorkSpace is ready!

*WorkSpace Login:*
* Registration Code: \[Get from AWS Console - see instructions below\]
* Username: {{ORG\<username>}}
* Password: \[Provide securely - see password lookup instructions below\]

*To connect:*
# Download Amazon WorkSpaces client from: [https://clients.amazonworkspaces.com/]
# Open the client and enter the registration code
# Log in with your credentials above

*Your WorkSpace includes:*
* S: drive with software installers
* Local administrator access for installing software

If you have issues, contact the IT team.
{panel}

h3. Get Registration Code

{code:language=bash}
aws workspaces describe-workspaces \
  --region ap-southeast-1 \
  --query "Workspaces[?UserName=='<username>'].{User:UserName,State:State,RegCode:ComputerName}" \
  --output table
{code}

Or find it in AWS Console → WorkSpaces → Directory → Registration Code

h3. Retrieve User Password

{info:title=Password Retrieval}
User passwords should be communicated securely to the end user. Retrieve the default password from:

*Option 1: Check users.yml*
{code:language=bash}
cat ~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/account-111122223333/ansible/playbooks/user-management/users.yml | grep default_password
{code}

*Option 2: AWS Secrets Manager*
{code:language=bash}
aws secretsmanager get-secret-value \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --secret-id org-infrastructure/credentials \
  --query SecretString --output text | jq .
{code}

*Best Practice:* Communicate passwords via a secure channel (e.g., encrypted email, password manager share, or in-person). Never send passwords in plain text emails.
{info}

----

h2. Quick Reference Commands

{expand:title=List All AD Users}
{code:language=bash}
cd ~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/account-111122223333/ansible
ansible-playbook playbooks/user-management/list-users.yml
{code}
{expand}

{expand:title=Reset User Password}
{code:language=bash}
aws ssm send-command \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --instance-ids i-0e5f7fdd4219cc530 \
  --document-name "AWS-RunPowerShellScript" \
  --parameters 'commands=["Set-ADAccountPassword -Identity <USERNAME> -Reset -NewPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString \"<NEW_PASSWORD>\" -AsPlainText -Force)"]' \
  --output json
{code}
{expand}

{expand:title=Disable a User}
{code:language=bash}
cd ~/Repos/cloud_infrastructure/account-111122223333/ansible
ansible-playbook playbooks/user-management/manage-users.yml -e "user_action=disable"
{code}
{expand}

{expand:title=Reboot a WorkSpace}
{code:language=bash}
aws workspaces reboot-workspaces \
  --region ap-southeast-1 \
  --reboot-workspace-requests WorkspaceId=<WORKSPACE_ID>
{code}
{expand}

{expand:title=Check WorkSpace Status}
{code:language=bash}
aws workspaces describe-workspaces \
  --region ap-southeast-1 \
  --query "Workspaces[*].{User:UserName,State:State,IP:IpAddress}" \
  --output table
{code}
{expand}

----

h2. Troubleshooting

{expand:title=User Can't Log In to WorkSpace}
*1. Verify AD account is enabled:*
{code:language=bash}
aws ssm send-command \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --instance-ids i-0e5f7fdd4219cc530 \
  --document-name "AWS-RunPowerShellScript" \
  --parameters 'commands=["Get-ADUser -Identity <USERNAME> -Properties Enabled | Select Enabled"]' \
  --output json
{code}

*2. Reset password if needed* (see Quick Reference above)

*3. Check AD Connector health* in AWS Console → Directory Service
{expand}

{expand:title=User Doesn't Have Local Admin Rights}
# Verify user is in {{WorkSpaces-LocalAdmins}} group (Step 2)
# If recently added, reboot the WorkSpace to apply GPO
# Force GPO update on WorkSpace:
#* Log in as user
#* Open CMD as admin: {{gpupdate /force}}
{expand}

{expand:title=S: Drive Not Appearing}
# Check if RcloneS3Mount service is running:
#* On WorkSpace: {{Get-Service RcloneS3Mount}}
# If not running, manually trigger:
#* Run {{\\example.internal\NETLOGON\Mount-S3-Drive.ps1}} as admin
# Check logs: {{C:\Windows\Temp\s3-mount.log}}
{expand}

{expand:title=WorkSpace Stuck in PENDING}
* Wait up to 20 minutes for initial provisioning
* If stuck longer, check AWS Console for error messages
* Verify AD Connector is healthy
{expand}

